The losers remain challengers
HARARE: I was convinced that irregularities in the elections this month would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they received terrorism.
In the two years that led to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe became victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is the responsibility of the villainous elements among the veterans from Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias and young men, who are all supported by the police.
The result of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in large parts, particularly the rural areas.
Furthermore, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, has effectively disempowered hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, without being able to cast their ballots into the ballot box.
I continue to question the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from deploying election observers at 52% of rural polling stations.
Towards the end of the election, our party lacked observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the rural areas.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were controlled solely by ZANU supporters.
In our preliminary investigations, a pattern has already become evident at this early stage: in these polling stations, the majority of votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the results of the presidential elections, from which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is in their eyes illegitimate.
The people of Zimbabwe had their right to freely and democratically elect their president taken away.
The struggle over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were courageous and determined and deserve to have this recognized.
Perhaps it is not too late yet.
I am writing this text in sorrow, for Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
Possibly, the government wants to arrest me.
I was already arrested for high treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the people's will to reclaim their rights and power.
It lies in our hands to carry out a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow ourselves to be overwhelmed by despair.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to see through what we have begun together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who were not driven away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very rocky path together to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely had to endure such violence and yet have managed to preserve kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand.
But for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot just leave these elections as they are, but they must also not fall for Mugabe's provocations and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all the obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that in all of Africa, elections are rigged.
In most African countries, irregularities, fraud, and deception in elections seem to be the norm.
In Africa, there is always some crisis due to elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it is time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest distress.
I pledge not to abandon it.
